If you’re a creator working with brands, READ THIS before you say yes to any collaboration ⬇

Here are non-negotiable steps to protect yourself and your content:

✅ Always communicate via official brand emails
Don’t rely on WhatsApp or DMs. If they’re serious, they’ll use a proper domain email (not @gmail, @outlook, etc.).

📝 Mention content rights clearly in writing
Specify:
— How long they can use your content
— No reuse, repurpose, or paid ads beyond the agreed timeline
— No edits without approval

📅 Track timelines like a pro
Set reminders for when your content should stop running. When the period ends, send a follow-up email to confirm they’ve taken everything down.

🧾 Document everything
From the first message to final deliverables — keep proof. Screenshots, emails, contracts — everything matters.

⚠ If they avoid written agreements or push back on terms — that’s your sign to walk away.

Let’s talk about something that barely gets spoken about on social media — the truth behind those “miracle” ₹200 pharmacy creams 🧴⚠️

You’ll see influencers swearing by these creams to clear acne, pigmentation, and textured skin — claiming they’re budget-friendly and life-changing. But here’s the part they don’t share (and you absolutely need to know):

✨ They often pair those creams with expensive skin-barrier-protecting serums, calming moisturizers, and non-stripping cleansers.
✨ Many take internal supplements — think zinc, omega-3s, and probiotics — to keep their skin clear from the inside.
✨ They don’t expose their skin to sun or heat during treatment. Instead, they stay indoors in air-conditioned spaces to avoid sensitivity.
✨ And let’s be honest — some may not even use the product consistently themselves, but promote it because it’s “relatable.” 😶

Now imagine trying that same cream without all of that protective care in place — hello, redness, peeling, and sensitized skin.🤷🏻‍♂️

So, whenever you try a new trending cream, make sure to do your research 🤝🏻
